The goal of this project  is to create an esolang bc I really like them.
The base principle is that every instruction has a timestamp at which it will be executed.
The whole program run on a simulated clock.

Instruction set
SUB A B → 4  
    B = A - B
ADD A B → 4
    A = A + B
MOV A B → 2  
    B = A
NEG A B → 3  
    B = -A
PRINT A B → 2  
    prints A
INPUT A B → 2  
    reads input into B

Operands:
- `@x` refers to variable `x`
- `x` without `@` is treated as a literal except when it's in the position B
- Values are converted to integers when possible at runtime

Timestamp conflicts:
If multiple instructions share the same timestamp:
- Let I1 be the instruction with the smallest line number
- Let I2 be the instruction with the largest line number
Execute I1 first.
If the result of I1 is negative:
    Execute I2
    Set the global time to the result of I2 (jump)
Otherwise:
    I2 is ignored

/!\ to make it more fun program lines must be spaced in timestamp space by at least 6 units.